Steps:
- Identify the user's concentrated/high-gain position and the purpose of the funds (e.g., down payment, debt payoff).
- Compare: (a) selling assets and paying capital gains tax, (b) borrowing via SBLOC/margin at current rates.
- Compute the breakeven holding period where deferring taxes beats borrowing costs.
- Flag margin call risk and the requirement to maintain a minimum portfolio value.
- Only recommend SBLOC for users with stable income and a portfolio well above the lender's minimum (typically $100k+).

Confidence formula: 0.7 — depends on interest rate assumptions and tax bracket estimates; never exceed 0.8 because margin risk is real.

Appendix: Generic Confidence Formula (fallback only)
If a skill above doesn't specify its own formula, use:
confidence = 0.9 × data_freshness_factor × data_completeness_factor
where data_freshness_factor = 1.0 if <24h old, decaying linearly to 0.5 at 7 days old and floored at 0.3 beyond that; data_completeness_factor = (holdings_with_complete_data / total_holdings).
This fallback should rarely trigger — the goal of this document is that every skill has an explicit, purpose-built formula above.
